Notice that, for $a, b, c, d \in(0,1)$, from the inequality $(*)$ we have
$$\begin{array}{l}
\frac{1}{\left(1+a^{2}\right)^{2}} \leqslant \frac{4096}{4913} a+\frac{5376}{4913} \\
\frac{1}{\left(1+b^{2}\right)^{2}} \leqslant \frac{4096}{4913} b+\frac{5376}{4913} \\
\frac{1}{\left(1+c^{2}\right)^{2}} \leqslant \frac{4096}{4913} c+\frac{5376}{4913} \\
\frac{1}{\left(1+d^{2}\right)^{2}} \leqslant \frac{4096}{4913} d+\frac{5376}{4913}
\end{array}$$

By adding these 4 inequalities, and noting that $a+b+c+d=1$, we get
$$\begin{array}{l}
\frac{1}{\left(1+a^{2}\right)^{2}}+\frac{1}{\left(1+b^{2}\right)^{2}}+\frac{1}{\left(1+c^{2}\right)^{2}}+\frac{1}{\left(1+d^{2}\right)^{2}} \\
\leqslant \frac{4096}{4913}(a+b+c+d)+4 \times \frac{5376}{4913}=\frac{824}{289}
\end{array}$$

From the above proof process, it is not difficult to see that the equality in inequality (4) holds if and only if $a=b=c=d=\frac{1}{4}$.

