Let $z=\sin ^{2} \alpha, \sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}=\cos ^{2} \alpha, x=\cos ^{2} \alpha \sin \beta, y=\cos ^{2} \alpha \cos \beta, \alpha, \beta \in\left(0, \frac{\pi}{2}\right]$,
then $x y+2 x z=x(y+2 z)=\cos ^{2} \alpha \sin \beta\left(\cos ^{2} \alpha \cos \beta+2 \sin ^{2} \alpha\right)$
$$
\begin{array}{l}
